What is FSLogix App Rule set?

Ruleset files are a collection of rules that show, hide, redirect, or customize specific aspects of registry, file system.

These Ruleset files are created by the FSLogix Apps RuleEditor and are processed by FSLogix Apps Service (frxsvc).

Types of Rules

Apprules are of three types:

i/ Hiding rule.

ii/ Redirection rule.

iii/ Specify value Rule.

Hiding Rule

A Hiding rule hides specific items from a user or group of users. Hiding rules can apply to files, folders, registry keys, Registry values, printers or fonts.

Redirection Rule

Redirection rules allows IT administrators to redirect non-profile or other specific data into user profile container.

So, it's available on subsequent sign ins regardless of which virtual machine they sign into.

Specify value rule

The specify value rule will, at signin, set a registry value for a specific user or group of users.

This rule is most commonly used when users need HKLM-based registry key values to change based on which users are signing in.

Note: FSLogix Apps Rule set assignments don't support Microsoft Entra ID cloud-only acco

Application rule sets are assigned to following entities:

user,group,Process,Network locations (IP address),Computer,Directory container (distinguished name),Environment Variable.

Newly created rules automatically have the Everyone group assigned with the Applies setting configured to NO.

There can be multiple assignments created in one Rule set.

The Rule set is applied from top to bottom.

Basic Troubleshooting for profile container

Profile container:

check local group membership (Exclude or include group)

check the registry settings for "enabled" and VHD location (CCD location)

HKLM\SOFTWARE\FSLOGIX\PROFILE

check to ensure the correct permissions are assigned to the user on the fileshare.

   the VHD location should be accessible by the user(RW).

check if a local profile doesn't already exists for a user.

check if the user doesn't have a disconnected session.

check the profile logs in %Programdata%\FSLogix\Logs\Profile.

ODFC Container

check local group membership (Exclude or include group)

check the registry setting for "enabled", and VHD location (FCD location)

HKLM\Software\Policies\FSLogix\ODFC

check to ensure the correct permissions are assigned to the user on fileshare.

   the VHD location should be accessible by the user(RW).

check windows search service is running.

Validate the outlook GPO settings

check the ODFC log files at %Programdata%\FSLogix\Logs\ODFC

FSLogix Deployment

i/ onpremise

On supported windows machine install FSLogix using FSLogix Appsetup.

configuring can be possible into two ways:

i/ GPO

ii/ Registry

If using GPO for configuration (FSLogix), we need to add the FSLogix.admx and FSLogix.adml files to the %sysvol%\PolicyDefination and %sysvol%\PolicyDefination\en-US respectively.

This will add the policy template to the local group policy.

Create a File share and share with users (allow Read/write).

Configure below GPOs:

Enabled : Set to Enabled and select Enabled.

VHD location : Set to Enabled and specify the path of the file share.

(e.g: \Fileserver.domain.com\fileshare).

Set optional GPOs such as:

Delete local Profile when VHD should apply

Volume Type

Prevent login with Temp Profile.

Prevent login with failure

Size in MB.

(Also: VHD Location and ProfileType)

Ensure that the user is member of the "FSLogix Profile include Group" in the local user groups (By default Everyone is added)

  It is recommended to add the Administrators to the "FSLogix Profile Exclude group" for Troubleshooting purpose.

Login to the configured windows machine using the account added to the FSLogix include group.

User should have FSLogix Profile created and loaded.

